Using JUnit 4.4 you can use `assertThat()` together with the [Hamcrest][1] code (don&#39;t worry, it&#39;s shipped with JUnit, no need for an extra `.jar`) to produce complex self-describing asserts including ones that operate on collections:

    import static org.junit.Assert.assertThat;
    import static org.junit.matchers.JUnitMatchers.*;
    import static org.hamcrest.CoreMatchers.*;
    
    List&lt;String&gt; l = Arrays.asList(&quot;foo&quot;, &quot;bar&quot;);
    assertThat(l, hasItems(&quot;foo&quot;, &quot;bar&quot;));
    assertThat(l, not(hasItem((String) null)));
    assertThat(l, not(hasItems(&quot;bar&quot;, &quot;quux&quot;)));
    // check if two objects are equal with assertThat()
    
    // the following three lines of code check the same thing.
    // the first one is the &quot;traditional&quot; approach,
    // the second one is the succinct version and the third one the verbose one 
